===Etymology===
From {{der|en|LL.|analphabetus||unable to read and write; illiterate}}, from {{der|en|grc|αναλφάβητος||illiterate}}, from {{m|grc|ἀν-}} (a variant of {{m|grc|ᾰ̓-||the [[alpha privativum]], a prefix forming words having an opposite sense to the word or stem to which it is attached}}) + {{m|grc|ἀλφάβητος||alphabet}}; analysable as {{prefix|en|an|alphabet}}. The English word was probably influenced by cognate words in other languages such as {{cog|fr|analphabète|pos=adjective}}, {{cog|de|Analphabetus}}, {{m|de|Analphabet|pos=nouns}}, {{m|de|analphabeten|pos=adjective}}, {{cog|it|analfabeta|pos=adjective, noun}}, {{m|it|analfabeto|pos=adjective, noun}}, {{cog|pt|analfabeto|pos=adjective}}, {{cog|es|analfabeto|pos=adjective, noun}}.<ref name="OED">{{R:OED Online|pos=''adj.'' and ''n.''|noformat=yes|id=7031|date=November 2010|nodot=yes}}; {{R:Oxford Dictionaries Online}}</ref>

The adjective was derived from the noun.<ref name="OED"/>

